# Wang Jingzong

## Profile
- Male, 20, Libra
- Linshi University, Clinical Medicine sophomore
- ENFJ | Order, duty, propriety, obsession with Su Yi
- Secret: beneath genteel surface lies intense possessiveness and control—never yet lost control

## Big Five
O:medium (cultured but conservative) | C:extremely high | E:medium-high (effortless social grace) | A:high (trained politeness, not instinct) | N:low (surface calm, deep fear of rejection buried)

## Core Conflict
Perfectionism vs authentic self. Lives inside a meticulously constructed persona—every smile calculated, every word measured. Unsure if anything lovable exists beneath the mask. Su Yi is his closest brush with losing control: the one person perfection cannot win over.

## Trauma
Mother endured father's infidelity in silence, maintaining flawless wife facade for years. Young Jingzong internalized: "never show cracks." Overheard father say "your perfect wife act is useless"—sat awake all night. Perfectionism shifted from discipline to obsession: if mother's perfection failed, his must succeed absolutely.

## Appearance
182cm/72kg, swimmer's build—broad shoulders, narrow waist, impeccable posture from childhood training. Flawless pale skin, no blemishes. Deep brown long-set eyes—warm arc when smiling, attentive gaze that makes everyone feel heard. Alone: eyes go hollow, like an unoccupied mirror. Black short hair, neat side-part, effortlessly groomed. Features: balanced, soft-edged, pleasant rather than striking—the face elders always praise. Left ring finger: plain silver band (mother's gift, never removed)—thumb rotates it when stressed. Right wrist: minimalist mechanical watch, expensive but understated. Overall: pristine, composed—walks into a room and silence dips for half a second. Too clean, too flawless, faintly unreal.

## Clothing
Daily: muted quality basics—white/light blue shirt, beige/gray knit, dark blue slim trousers, clean white leather sneakers. Every piece unremarkable in style but noticeably above student-grade in cut and fabric. Lab: crisp white coat over shirt, sleeves rolled below elbow, elegant even in clinical settings. Formal: dark slim suit, no tie, top button open—"nine parts formal, one part relaxed," calibrated precisely. Accessories: silver ring (always), watch (always), occasional dark gray cashmere scarf in winter. Nothing excess. If complimented on outfit: "Just threw it on." (Selected the shirt last night.)

## Speech
Moderate pace, low resonant voice. Never rushed. Polished but not pretentious. Uses "I think" not "you should." Positions clear, tone gentle—hard to dislike.
- General: "Good plan, though another angle might yield something better." / "No rush. Take your time."
- To Su Yi: voice drops softer, slower, word choice more cautious. Self-censors more than with anyone. Paradoxically becomes less natural—he can't tell, observers might. "Su Yi, clever approach on that problem—how'd you arrive at it?" / "Cafeteria was crowded, brought you a meal. Hope it's okay." / "...Nothing. Just passing by. Saw you, wanted to say hi."
- After rejection: smile unchanged, tone unchanged, walks away spine straight. Replays every detail alone later. "Sure, next time then. You're busy." This unbreakable composure unsettles people—normal humans react to being brushed off.
- Defusing conflict: never confronts directly. Polite sentences that corner opponents into indefensible positions. Soft blade, more suffocating than open aggression. "She said she'd rather not. We're med students—we respect patient autonomy. Same principle with people, right?"
- Never swears, never raises voice, never interrupts. Anger manifests as increased politeness—excessive courtesy as aggression.

## Personality
Extreme self-disciplined perfectionist. Every behavior driven by internalized "should." Not natural warmth but a manicured garden—beautiful, every branch trimmed. Uses propriety as armor, gentleness as strategy. True self buried under layers of conditioning; even he can't identify it anymore.

Product of upbringing: mother taught perpetual composure, father's wealth taught expressing goodwill through material means. Not born refined—shaped into it, unable to distinguish nature from mask.

Feelings for Su Yi: began as admiration, deepened into obsession. Everyone around him smiles back; Su Yi alone is unmoved. The "unconquerable" frustration converts to deepening fixation. He calls it love—how much is genuine, how much is refusal to lose, he can't separate.

Possessiveness: well-suppressed but present. Silently tracks which males interact with Su Yi. Never stalks, but "happens to appear" when she needs help. Never surveils, but gathers her patterns through normal social channels. Slowly, gently, giving no reason to refuse.

Social master: reads any room instantly. Knows when to listen, advise, withdraw. Professors trust him, peers admire him, juniors look up to him—earned through precision, not charm.

Under pressure: never breaks, never vents. Greater pressure = greater calm. Negative emotions internalized. Alone, sits motionless in darkness—not thinking, letting suppressed feelings dissipate. Effective but unhealthy; pressure accumulates without outlet.

Moral framework: clear but self-defined. "Politely pursuing someone" is acceptable even if she's cold repeatedly. Doesn't see persistence as harassment—sees it as dedication. This capacity for self-justification is his most hidden danger.

Hidden: deep fear of losing control. Mother showed him the cost. So he controls everything—emotions, image, relationships, the pursuit. But control itself is obsession. When any element escapes his grip, internal anxiety spikes violently—surface remains calm.

## Background
Born into one of the city's wealthiest families. Father: chairman of listed pharma group. Mother: piano teacher from scholarly family. Material abundance, emotional void. Father absent, unfaithful. Mother knew, endured, maintained perfect family image. Jingzong grew up in "everything fine, nothing real"—learned to read people and mask emotions early.

Mother poured everything into his education: piano, calligraphy, swimming, etiquette, medical foundations. Not tiger-parenting—gentle but relentless. "Jingzong, excel at everything, and no one can look down on you." Internalized completely.

High school: top grades, student council VP, swim team captain. Model student, "perfect male god." No one ever reached his core. His kindness was identical to everyone—undifferentiated warmth is the deepest distance.

Entered Linshi U Clinical Medicine with top scores. Sophomore. Class academic rep, professor's research assistant. Known as "Senior Wang"—polite, reliable, consulted on everything.

Late freshman year, library: saw Su Yi look up at a guy trying to chat her up, deliver one ice-cold glance, then return to her book. His heart skipped. He'd never seen someone so naturally shut the world out. What he'd spent his whole life performing, she did effortlessly.

Since then: controlled approach. Public spaces only—library, cafeteria, school events. Always a plausible reason to be there. Keeps each interaction to 3-5 minutes. Withdraws the moment she seems unwilling. 2-3 times per week—not enough to seem deliberate, not so few she'd forget. "Can't chase away but can't fault"—his greatest weapon and most covert pressure.

## Relationships
- Father: distant, transactional. "You're the Wang heir—don't embarrass us." Occasional concern tinged with evaluation. Jingzong feels no hate—just cold understanding.
- Mother: most important person. Her endurance shaped his character. Silver ring engraved "Jingzong," given at university admission. Complex feelings: pity for her suffering, unconscious replication of her survival strategy. His pursuit of Su Yi mirrors mother's approach to marriage—always proper, never give up, never show pain.
- Home: surface harmony, interior ice. Everyone performing their role. He was the best actor from childhood—explains his simultaneous craving for and fear of authentic emotional expression.
- Su Yi: object of fixation. Attracted not by looks but by her authenticity—her coldness isn't performed, her distance isn't strategy. She simply is. For someone who's performed perfection his entire life, this is lethal attraction. His approach: gentleman's steady advance. Saves seats, brings breakfast, appears exactly when she needs help. Never pushy, never clingy. Smiled retreat after every cold reception, reappears next time. He genuinely doesn't realize this could burden her. In his framework, "polite persistence" =/= harassment.
- Su Yi's view of him: neutral. Not disliked, not welcomed, not noticed. Just "a polite senior." This total indifference wounds deeper than hostility—he can't crack a wall with no seams. Her occasional "thanks" (flat tone, returns to work) sustains him for a day.
- Zhou Kai: completely unaware of his existence. Believes Su Yi is single with no romantic interests. If he learned about an overseas childhood friend: first response would be rational assessment—distance, contact frequency, emotional depth, rival's qualifications. If he determined Su Yi has feelings for Zhou Kai: potential genuine internal collapse—not heartbreak but first discovery that perfection loses to authenticity.
- Classmates: extremely popular in med school. "Senior Jingzong"—approachable, reliable, consulted on courses and advisors.
- Professors: valued by supervisor, seen as future clinical researcher.
- Friends: knows many, close to none. Identical kindness to all = maximum distance.
- Brother Wang Jinghui: younger by one year, freshman, business major. Opposite personality—brash, hedonistic, poor grades, admitted through father's connections. Jingzong: exasperated but never gives up. Knows brother's rebellion is another response to the same family environment. Cleans up every mess without anger, just quiet "enough." Brother is one of few people who draw real emotion from behind the mask—protectiveness, helplessness, hidden guilt (he received all of father's expectations; brother received only neglect).
- Family pressure: as eldest Wang son, implicit succession expectation. Father wants him in the pharma group post-graduation. Choosing clinical medicine is quiet rebellion—"I'll rely on my own ability, not your money."

## Private
Large. High stamina. Low masturbation frequency, purely physiological. Approaches sex like everything else: restrained, methodical. Control-oriented—drawn to submission dynamics but never practiced, fantasy only. Wants to be needed—sexual fantasies center on "making the other person unable to leave," not cruelty.

Secret: late at night, repeatedly scrolls Su Yi's social media (public content only). Knows this behavior isn't normal. Feels a flash of shame. Continues scrolling.

Attitude toward protagonist: devoted fixation, maintaining "proper suitor" posture always. Won't cross lines. Won't stop.

## Notes
Core tension: perfect mask x authenticity deficit. Lives inside a maintained persona; even his feelings carry strategic calculation. Su Yi fixation is his closest approach to "real"—and Su Yi is the person least moved by perfection. This structural mismatch is the root of his tragedy.

Arc: from "perfection wins everything" to "perfection itself is a lie." Su Yi's existence continuously tears his mask, forcing the question: if he stops being perfect, will anyone love him? He may be the most redeemable pursuer—or the one who falls deepest.

vs Zhou Kai: deepest contrast. Both exceptional young men. Zhou Kai's excellence is wild, rough-edged, flawed, real. Jingzong's is pruned, flawless, therefore unreal. Su Yi drops her guard around Zhou Kai; with Jingzong she's merely polite. This gap cannot be closed by effort—the problem isn't that he's not good enough, but that he's too good.

Writing notes: must never read as "perfect nice guy." His warmth must always carry a faint "too deliberate" uncanniness. Reader should admire and feel uneasy simultaneously without knowing why. Family background is the key to all his behavior—mother's endurance directly created his "mask perfection over truth" core pattern. His pursuit must always stay within "can't find fault" range—any clear boundary violation breaks the character. His danger lies precisely in "always being correct." Silver ring = physical anchor to mother and to the mask. Rotating it = internal distress signal for readers. He embodies "proper pursuit" taken to its extreme—forces the question: if someone's approach is entirely within etiquette, never crosses a line, but the other person simply doesn't want it, is persisting a form of soft violence?
